// Nalia1

@98 = ~Will you tell me something, Yikari? You monks learn the secrets of the Universe, you grow wise, but most of you never leave your monasteries. How can you do anyone any good that way?~

@99 = ~Nalia, we do not seek enlightenment for others; it is an internal process we undertake. It cannot be done in the stressful world outside of an introspective monastery.~

@100 = ~But you should still try to bring peace to others! There ought to be wandering monks, like priests, helping those they find.~

@101 = ~There are some monks who venture out into the world. This is not the first time I have been in foreign parts, although I never heard of any monk journeying this far west.~

@102 = ~Our way of life is not for all, and we do not owe it to anyone to teach them, unless they come to learn.~

@103 = ~Then why do you teach at all?~

@104 = ~I only let others teach themselves. I cannot do more than they are willing or able. Come now, we should not tarry.~

// Nalia2

@105 = ~Nalia? Making yourself invisible is a skill which you practise, both by magic and trick of eye, is it not?~

@106 = ~Why yes, that is one thing I can do.~

@107 = ~Then let me impart to you an observation I have made whilst in Athkatla:~

@108 = ~If you ask others for money, you become invisible.~

@109 = ~But- but that's horrible! I always give to beggars!~

@110 = ~Perhaps that is why you are so conspicuous.~



// Edwin1

@111 = ~Tell me, monk, have you ever seen a wizard more capable, more powerful, and more virile than I, Edwin Odesseron?~

@112 = ~I have seen few mages in my travels, so I suppose I must answer in the negative.~

@113 = ~Of course you must: there is none greater than myself (except perhaps... no, not even him!).~

@114 = ~I find that a little hard to believe, Edwin.~

@115 = ~I am so good I could throw you a Scorcher and only singe your hair (Yes, make that carefully manicured bun of hair fry).~

@116 = ~Perhaps so, but what good is that against a well aimed kick or blade?~

@117 = ~*This* mage shall never be thwarted by the methods of such simpletons (simians all). My immense magical skill shall both protect me and turn my foes into so much dust.~

//Edwin2

@118 = ~Edwin?~

@119 = ~Yes, you dusty Eastern dancer? (he is no more than a blur of dirty feet when he fights) Why do you disturb my schemes?~

@120 = ~Pardon me for asking, but why do you... talk to yourself?~

@121 = ~I don't know what you're talking about (no idea)! I think aloud (yes, he's right!), I think aloud!~

@122 = ~How dare you question my sanity! Try it again and I shall turn you into something small and unpleasant (a smoked kipper, perhaps?)!~

@123 = ~I never questioned your sanity... but perhaps it would be better if I were just silent?~

@124 = ~Yes! Cease your incessant ramblings about us (ME! You mean me!). Yes, stop talking about me (that's better)!~

// Edwina1

@125 = ~Stop staring at me! If I find your eyes on me again I shall have them taken out!~

@126 = ~I was just ruminating on how your desire for power corrupted your form.~

@127 = ~If you had been content with what you, at least, thought to be impressive power, then you would not now be transformed.~

@128 = ~This is but a mere mishap in my destiny, and I will not be ridiculed by such as you (cursed monkey)!~

@129 = ~As you say.~

@130 = ~(Dammit, he got the last word)~



// Jan1

@131 = ~My Uncle Johan went to Kara-Tur once, Yikari.~

@132 = ~Oh really?~

@133 = ~He was trying to open up new markets for the turnip trade, but unfortunately he ran into difficulties. It was all due to an underground cavern beneath his stall, which was inhabited once a month by a horde of estate agents; and by the time they had picked up each other and left by the Planar Express, his customers were so terrified that they eventually called a certified vegetable merchant to inspect him.~

@134 = ~I... see. Go on.~

@135 = ~Well, after that, everything went a bit turnip-shaped, if you know what I mean. It was all he could do not to traffic in illegal rice, calling to mind the unfortunate case of Great Aunt Winny, who was soundly spanked for smuggling a peanut shipment into Waterdeep, without, I might add, a single rogue turnip, or "Stealth-o-Turnips", as we call them in the trade. Anyway, this fish that Uncle Willie had caught-~

@136 = ~Fish? What fish?~

@137 = ~Why, the fish that made his fortune, of course! It was worth its weight in turnips, since it gave him the idea that revolutionized the whole fishing industry! That's how the fishing rod was invented, you know. Some insisted it had been developed independently in every early coastal community in the Realms, but it was first patented by Uncle Willie, I assure you. Did I ever tell you Cousin Archie was an inventor?~

@138 = ~Jan, a year with you would drive me mad or teach me boundless patience. However, please be silent for a while, or a hasty blow will mean neither of us will ever find out which.~

// Jan2

@139 = ~So, Yikky, I believe I was telling you about the time my cousin was nearly eaten by two ogres outside Baldur's Gate?~

@140 = ~Jan, my name is Yikari. Please address me by the same.~

@141 = ~Please, Yikky, don't interrupt a gnome when he's telling a story. So, there he was, being held by two ogres, and as you know, my Cousin can talk the ears off a donkey, so he tries to stall them by telling them the tale of Second Cousin Margen. She, Margen, was running from the Watch of Neverwinter at the time, though perhaps she could have made things less confusing all round by telling them first. You see: it isn't that she *meant* to take that money: it just found its way into her coffers, just like that. The Vegetable Traders' Guild was most displeased, I assure you. Displeased with her, not the Watch, you understand.~

@142 = ~Jan, what exactly are you trying to say to me? And my name is Yikari.~

@143 = ~Hm? Did you want something?~

@144 = ~I- never mind (sigh).~



// Haer'Dalis1

@145 = ~Haer'Dalis, as a poet, do you know any Haiku?~

@146 = ~Haiku, my owl? What is that?~

@147 = ~Ah, I am surprised that you do not know about Haiku.~

@148 = ~It is the form of poetry we have in Kara-Tur. Three lines: five, seven then five syllables in them. They don't rhyme, unlike this foreign poetry.~

@149 = ~Most interesting... Aye, I do try to dip my creative feet into the many pools of Prime poetry.~

@150 = ~Once I have assembled a haiku worthy for your mountain home, dear owl, I shall give it to you for your slow contemplation. I trust you appreciate the beauty of words, my dear owl?~

@151 = ~Yes: Haiku is a common form of seeking enlightenment, for peace and understanding can be found outside our bodies, in the rifts of mountains to the blossom of trees.~

@152 = ~Mabye my stern owl does have a poet's soul, "karma" rather, after all!~

// Haer'Dalis2

@153 = ~Haer'Dalis... without meaning to offend, why do you call me "your owl" when you know my name to be Yikari?~

@154 = ~Is my owl displeased with his name? Does an owl not suit?~

@155 = ~But why do you name all your companions after birds or animals? Why the fascination?~

@156 = ~I choose birds' names because they demonstrate the fleeting existence you Primes have.~

@157 = ~Names earned are worth more than those given at birth. Miss Raelis taught me that.~

@158 = ~It is not, then, an... affectation?~

@159 = ~What a suggestion from my own true owl! You too have a bard's eye, I think.~



// Keldorn1

@160 = ~Friend, am I to take it that your Order does good works much like my own of the Radiant Heart?~

@161 = ~Sir Keldorn, I believe you misunderstand. Though I do come from an Order, that of the Green Dragon, we have little in common with you western Paladins.~

@162 = ~You try to serve your god Torm, to help others in the city, but our monastery is secluded from civilisation. We seek self-enlightenment, not your "justice". Also for us martial arts is a discipline to hone mind and body, not just a method of incapacitating others.~

@163 = ~Do you mean to say that your order just rests in their mountain monastery and ignores the world's injustice? I have heard the monks of Kara-Tur called wise, yet that strikes me as terribly blind!~

@164 = ~Sir Keldorn, I am sorry if I have offended you-~

@165 = ~Enough. We should not debate. <CHARNAME> has use of my blade, and I must attend!~

// Keldorn2

@166 = ~Yikari, do you not see that your introspective lifestyle leaves you ignorant of the world outside of your monastery’s walls?~

@167 = ~Why do you antagonise me so, Keldorn? My life has been no less honourable than yours, regardless that I have no foreign title.~

@168 = ~You cannot excuse yourself from your duty to others by ignoring it.~

@169 = ~What duty do you mean?~

@170 = ~The duty to help those less fortunate than ourselves, by Torm!~

@171 = ~I know only the duty to my superior and liege-<LADYLORD>, at present <CHARNAME>. Why should any other be my concern?~

@172 = ~I can see you have led a want-free life, else you would not act so callously.~

@173 = ~I can only act and think as I have learnt to do. If I pain you thus, Sir Keldorn, then I shall keep my speech to you behind my tongue.~




// Cernd1

@174 = ~Cernd, why do you voluntarily accept lycanthropy? Most men consider it a curse, but you seem to revel in it.~

@175 = ~Nature grants me the control necessary to make it a boon rather than a curse. The power and strength of my werewolf form give me the ability to overcome those who would harm Nature. It grants me the strength to battle foes normally beyond me.~

@176 = ~So it your control of your ability that cause you to see lycanthropy as blessing, where other men see only a disease?~

@177 = ~It is not so simple as that. It is also a form closer to Nature, more simple and less corrupt. Nature is allowing me to become more closely entwinned with Her.~

@178 = ~Thank you for enlightening me. I will think on what you have said.~

// Cernd2

@179 = ~Cernd, the power that nature grants to you seem to me highly flawed. You lose control of yourself - something so impure is surely bad karma?~

@180 = ~Yikari, you see only the surface of the matter. The power to shift my shape is a form of purity given to me as a gift for my services to Nature.~

@181 = ~What do you mean? You become less than a man. You lose all the discipline you have striven so hard to achieve.~

@182 = ~It is true that I become primal. When I shift form I am simply becoming closer to Nature - closer to the roots of myself. It is a more simple, less complicated form. You seek purity of body and soul - what is more pure than a creature of Nature? In some ways my shapechanging is very like your own quest for self perfection.~

@183 = ~But you relinquish your self-control. I see the value of what you claim, but with such an element of beast, how can it be pure?~

@184 = ~I lose my wisdom, but I gain strength and agility. I lose some things, but they are replaced by others. In my other form I simply have no need of knowledge - everything is resloved: all that matters is the moment and the battle. In my shifted form, I am in some ways more pure than you can ever be through your meditations and study!~

@185 = ~Yes... I see how that is a form of control, albeit a strange one. Thank you, Cernd.~



// Viconia1

@186 = ~I feel your eyes on me, abil. If you want to feel my body tonight, you need only beg.~

@187 = ~Viconia?~

@188 = ~Yes, male?~

@189 = ~I am celibate. You can redirect your advances to others if you wish.~

@190 = ~Celibate? What do you mean?~

@191 = ~I have sworn not to lie with anyone. It is a part of the sacrifice a monk makes to train his mind and body.~

@192 = ~WHAT- ssa n'taerreth neth'rar (mutter)...~

// Viconia2

@193 = ~So, monk, in your... "celibate" state, are you not constantly frustrated by every beautiful body you find?~

@194 = ~At first it was challenging, but now I find no difficulty in restraining my... animal urges.~

@195 = ~Ha! Don't deny the inevitable. You cannot help but find me irresistable! Damn you, monk!~

@196 = ~Viconia, I have no interest in you sexually. Please control yourself.~

@197 = ~If you have difficulty in dealing with your desires I am sure we can find someone for you in the next town.~

@198 = ~Ss'a ma'laeret mon'a ruth'gar! Ssa minit'rae!~



// Korgan1

@199 = ~Ye know, Yikari, ye do just fine in battle. I ne'er seen a longlimbs fight like ye do, but if ye can only do it after ye "meditashun" mumbo-jumbo, then ye can shove it where the sun don't shine.~

@200 = ~Well, my good dwarf, my training in the martial arts is just one of many disciplines which I have mastered in order to perfect my control of mind and body.~

@201 = ~Ach, I knew it! Do ye not just want te revel in the bloodlust when ye axe severs neck? I ain't ye "good dwarf" neither.~

@202 = ~I take no pleasure in death, though I do obtain satisfaction from the perfect execution of an exercise or manouevre.~

@203 = ~Bah! Ye're nothin' but a towel-wearing fool!~

// Korgan2

@204 = ~Hey monk, join me in a mug o' ale with me, next tavern we find.~

@205 = ~Ale? Alcohol leads to a loss of control and a dampening of inhibition. I fear I cannot, Korgan.~

@206 = ~What? Ye willna ha' a drop o' ale? What do ye damned monks do for fun?~

@207 = ~Well, I suppose... I don't know. I never thought about it.~

@208 = ~Of all the most hair-brained, crack-headed, foolish bunch of longlimbs, you monks have got to be the very worst!~


