// Mazzy1

@220 = ~Small one, may I ask a question of you?~

@221 = ~Small one? My good Yikari, I would prefer to be addressed by my name, which is Mazzy.~

@222 = ~Forgive me, Mazzy. I did not mean to offend.~

@223 = ~Not at all, sir. What did you want to know?~

@224 = ~Mazzy, I note that you are a warrior of some skill, and dedicated to the service of your god.~

@225 = ~I thank you for the compliment. I do strive to be a worthy servant of Avoreen.~

@226 = ~Yet you seem to crave recognition as a Paladin of this “Avoreen” from those outside of your race and faith.~

@227 = ~That is true. I would wish to be recognised as a Paladin.~

@228 = ~So my question is: why?~

@229 = ~I beg your pardon?~

@230 = ~Why do you crave such recognition?~

@231 = ~Yikari, this may be difficult for you to understand, but my people are, I fear, undervalued and underestimated by the great powers in this land.~

@232 = ~We are dismissed as farmers and merchants, and those few of us who pursue more adventurous lives are too often stereotyped as thieves. I wish to bring glory and recognition to my people and my god, to show the world that Halflings too can strive for justice, and for the right.~

@233 = ~Do you not see how hollow such recognition would be? Perfection of the self is all that matters, and that takes place entirely within.~

@234 = ~That may be true, good monk. Still, I must look beyond myself to serve my people, and in this world glory is no small thing.~



// Yoshimo1

@235 = ~Excuse me, are you THE Yoshimo? Feared by all?~

@236 = ~Why yes, good monk! See <CHARNAME>, I knew someone would know of me.~

@237 = ~Then tell me, Yoshimo, is it true what they say about the theft of the Grim Ankh of Morpork? I heard you crept past three-score guards and eluded capture!~

@238 = ~Ha! As I remember it was four-score, and I also had the time to seduce a few maidens on the job!~

@239 = ~And did you also take the fiery goblet from the hoard of Athor the brown wrym?~

@240 = ~All my work! Yes, yes! A true admirer at last, from Kara-Tur, no less!~

@241 = ~Then perhaps you can help me clear up a matter concerning them. I have researched your exploits, yet I can find no mention of any city of Morpork. Nor is Athor in the ancient lore-list of wyrms, as I have read.~

@242 = ~<CHARNAME>, you lived at Candlekeep. Surely you can enlighten our friend here (wink)?~

@243 = ~(Lie) Of course, the fabled lost city of Morpork! And the fierce wrym Athor, how great he was in the majesty! And I thought you learned, Yikari!~

@244 = ~(Truth) He's pulling your leg, Yikari. It's possible a little of what you have heard may have been... exaggerated over time.~

@245 = ~I thank you, for one never stops learning.~

@246 = ~Ah, how disappointing. Perhaps you will tell me sometime yourself, Yoshimo.~

@247 = ~Hah, of course, my friend.~

// Yoshimo2

@248 = ~Friend, what are those tattoos on your chest?~

@249 = ~It is a green dragon. I belong to the Order of the Green Dragon; the tattoos are a testament to that.~

@250 = ~The Order of the Green Dragon... I don't think I have heard of it.~

@251 = ~There is no reason you should have, if you are not a monk, that is. The monastery is in a valley between two small mountains. The views are beautiful, there are cherry blossoms in Spring and delicate snowfalls in winter.~

@252 = ~I should like to come visit your monastery, if it is really so wonderful.~

@253 = ~When all this is over, perhaps we shall journey back together.~



// Valygar1

@254 = ~If I may ask, Valygar, how did a man of the West come into a possession of such a fine weapon as Bleeder?~

@255 = ~I had an adventurous ancestor, Yikari. Not unlike you, he traveled far. The sword was a curiosity he brought home and when I was a child, I gazed at it hanging at the wall; the day I was tall enough to pull it free of the scabbard, I did.~

@256 = ~You did not request the permission of your elder?~

@257 = ~My tutor complained to my mother that morning that I was inattentive and wilful. My lady mother absent-mindedly sent me to my father, and my lord father was too exhausted by a fit of his sickness to care. He simply ordered me to go play while he talked to my over-zealous governor.~

@258 = ~A katana is a weapon which needs a man’s hand - it is no toy. Its master can take it free of its scabbard and decapitate a foe in one motion.~

@259 = ~Perhaps. But the boys who play with danger grow quicker than the cautious ones.~

@260 = ~No, Valygar, if a man was not trained in self-discipline, his life would be an eternal boyhood.~